dismissalText.commentary: Paul Stirling run out (Najibullah Zadran/Mujeeb Ur Rahman) 55 (87b 3x4 1x6 124m) SR: 63.21

dismissalComment.html: reverse-swept from middle stump to backward point's right. There's a horrible mix-up between the wickets. The throw from Najib is to the bowler. Mujeeb gathers it and breaks the bails to catch Stirling short. The well-set batsman has been run out. Stirling knew he was gone. The TV umpire confirms it. The last thing Ireland wanted is a run out

dismissalText.commentary: Mohammad Shahzad c Rankin b Simi Singh 54 (50b 6x4 2x6 66m) SR: 108

dismissalComment.html: Shahzad goes for one big hit too many and holes out to long-on. Skids on outside off, Simi Singh finds some extra bounce and forces the opener to fetch the slog-sweep from there. The batsman aimed to launch it over midwicket. He instead splices it straighter to Rankin. A little opening for Ireland?

dismissalText.commentary: Gulbadin Naib c McBrine b Rankin 45 (91b 3x4 0x6 115m) SR: 49.45

dismissalComment.html: top edge taken at point! Gulbadin has fallen just on the verge of what might have been Rankin's last ball of this spell. It's a short ball in the corridor and he looks to pull without shifting his weight backwards. Ends up wafting from underneath and it's a simple catch

commentPreTextItems.html: Afghanistan need one off the last over. This is all but over for Ireland and Zimbabwe

commentTextItems.html: Afghanistan qualify for the World Cup! Stanikzai punches his fist in the air repeatedly. Heartbreak for Ireland. Heartbreak for Zimbabwe. Off-stump yorker, Stanikzai jabs his bat down and sends a thick inside edge past the leg stump

commentPostTextItems.html: 5.05pm There we have our two qualifiers for the 2019 World Cup: West Indies and Afghanistan. Afghanistan's players collectively roar: "WE ARE IN!". Afghanistan had lost their first three games but then won four in a row to become the tenth and final team to qualify for the World Cup. Shahzad has already issued a warning to West Indies. Hope you enjoyed our coverage as much as we did bringing it to you. This is Deivarayan Muthu signing off on the behalf of Varun Shetty and P Ranjith. Cheers. Be back for the final on Sunday.
Hamid Seddiqi: "Whole Kabul is shaking with celebrations..."

5pm Let's hear from the two captains. Porterfield: First of all congratulations to Afghanistan. We were probably 25 runs short. Then again in games like this we can't fault anyone. We get back for some rest and recuperation. We had opportunities but we lost three games. We had some key moments but could not take it. Big things on the horizon.

Stanikzai: I am in too much pain but I was playing for the country. It is our dream to qualify for the World Cup. Afghanistan team played bad in first half but they played well and they believed in themselves.

4.45pm Who writes your scripts, Afghanistan? They did not have their captain Stanikzai in the league phase. Their key batsman Mohammad Shahzad was suspended for two matches. Their stand-in captain Rashid Khan said: "Sometimes a tournament doesn't go your way." They barely made it to the Super Sixes. Nepal then handed them a lifeline, then UAE handed them another lifeline. Afghanistan suffered a middle-order wobble today, and it looked like anybody's game in the end overs. Captain Stanikzai, coming back from a bout of appendicitis, eventually sealed Afghanistan's World Cup spot.

Shahzad, Man of the Match: We lost a couple of matches but we played good cricket in the Super Sixes. We had to win this game. The plan is simple: I was waiting for the loose ball and then I don't care. I just hit the boundaries. I believe in myself. The coaching staff say 'just play your natural game'. Oh! I can't believe we have qualified for the World Cup. Let's see West Indies, we are coming! (Shahzad points right at the camera)
Shahzad in #Bossmode. He's leading the Champyaan dance. Great scenes in the Afghanistan camp.
rb: "Amazing ! After loosing first 3 games, AFG needed to win all the rest & still required a very specific set of results in the other matches"

commentTextItems.html: short on middle stump, miscues a pull over midwicket. Scorers are level

commentPostTextItems.html: James: "Takes it to the final over. MS Dhoni in disguise!"

commentTextItems.html: short and rising into the body, the batsman rises with it, fends to point

commentPreTextItems.html: Ujjwal: "Miraclous performance by Afganistan throughout this tournament. They struggled to get into Super Sixes and now this. Brilliant!"

commentTextItems.html: on a length and outside off, dabbed away fine of third man. Stanikzai hobbles back for the second
Has Stanikzai feathered it behind? There's a little noise and Niall is excited. Back of a length and outside off, he cuts away from the body and misses
Najib backs away outside leg, this is darted short and wide outside off. Upper cut away over backward point
back of a length and sliding onto the leg stump, picked away fine of long leg. Balbirnie slides in the deep and hauls the ball back into the field of play. Just two in the end
chest-high short ball on middle, this is more a short-arm flap than a short-arm pull. The ball sneaks away to the leg side

headshotImage.longCaption: Tim Murtagh player page headshot cutout, 2021

headshotImage.longCaption: Boyd Rankin player page headshot cutout, 2021

commentTextItems.html: full and angling away outside off, right in the swinging arc, Najib clears his front leg and tonks it hiiiiiiiiiiiiigh over midwicket. Launched into the stands. He narrows the gap with a mighty blow
back of a length on off, cramps the batsman for room, clipped straight to short midwicket
back of a length and angling across off stump, swiped away to the right of long leg. Rankin isn't the quickest in the outfield and Afghanistan take two runs
on a length and on a fourth-stump line, whisked to short midwicket again. Down to a run a ball again

commentPreTextItems.html: Stanikzai needs some treatment. He had missed the start of the tournament because of a bout of appendicitis. Afghanistan need 16 off 18 balls
Aditya: "I reckon Ireland made a mistake by not giving Stirling some overs as spinners did make an impact."

commentTextItems.html: very full and attacking the stumps, Najib camps back and works the ball straight to short midwicket
shorter and outside off, glided away to the right of Simi now

commentTextItems.html: back of a length and slanting away outside off, punched crisply but Simi throws himself to his right from backward point to stop the ball
short on the hips, deflected behind square on the leg side. Stanikzai rushes back for the second and clutches his side
back of a length and hits the bat hard again as opposed to bat hitting ball. Defended to the off side
Rankin finds extra bounce and attacks the body, Najib looks away and splices it to point

commentPreTextItems.html: Afghanistan need 20 off 24 balls. They can breathe easy now. Can Rankin shake things up again. He runs in from over the wicket

commentTextItems.html: back of a length and outside off, extends his hands and carves it away to deep point for a single
very full on the pads, nudged to deep square leg

dismissalText.commentary: Paul Stirling run out (Najibullah Zadran/Mujeeb Ur Rahman) 55 (87b 3x4 1x6 124m) SR: 63.21

dismissalComment.html: reverse-swept from middle stump to backward point's right. There's a horrible mix-up between the wickets. The throw from Najib is to the bowler. Mujeeb gathers it and breaks the bails to catch Stirling short. The well-set batsman has been run out. Stirling knew he was gone. The TV umpire confirms it. The last thing Ireland wanted is a run out

dismissalText.commentary: Niall O'Brien c Samiullah Shinwari b Dawlat Zadran 36 (41b 4x4 1x6 44m) SR: 87.8

dismissalComment.html: overpitched and wide outside off, Niall stretches out and drives to the left of Shenwari at short extra cover. Niall plays an aerial drive instead of keeping it down. Dawlat returns and takes down Niall. Both set batsmen are gone now

dismissalText.commentary: Mohammad Shahzad c Rankin b Simi Singh 54 (50b 6x4 2x6 66m) SR: 108

dismissalComment.html: Shahzad goes for one big hit too many and holes out to long-on. Skids on outside off, Simi Singh finds some extra bounce and forces the opener to fetch the slog-sweep from there. The batsman aimed to launch it over midwicket. He instead splices it straighter to Rankin. A little opening for Ireland?

dismissalText.commentary: Gulbadin Naib c McBrine b Rankin 45 (91b 3x4 0x6 115m) SR: 49.45

dismissalComment.html: top edge taken at point! Gulbadin has fallen just on the verge of what might have been Rankin's last ball of this spell. It's a short ball in the corridor and he looks to pull without shifting his weight backwards. Ends up wafting from underneath and it's a simple catch

dismissalComment.html: chipped to short midwicket! Shah steps out and doesn't get to the pitch of the ball. He clips on the up and as a result he can't keep this down. It's straight to the fielder who takes a low catch

headshotImage.caption: Barry McCarthy player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Barry McCarthy player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Samiullah Shinwari c Wilson b McCarthy 27 (63b 2x4 0x6 78m) SR: 42.85

dismissalComment.html: McCarthy finds redemption. A very tense finish brewing in Harare. A World Cup spot is on the line. This was overpitched and outside off, instead of scything it over the boundary Shenwari slices it to backward point. Good, low catch under pressure from Wilson

headshotImage.caption: Simi Singh player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Mohammad Nabi c McBrine b Simi Singh 12 (24b 0x4 0x6 36m) SR: 50

dismissalComment.html: Simi Singh claims his third wicket and tightens the chase. This was fired in on middle, Simi pulled his length back after seeing Nabi foray down the track. He does not meet the pitch of the ball and winds up dragging a catch to deep midwicket

milestones.description: Porterfield has scored 26 fifty-plus scores in ODIs, the most for IRE breaking Paul Stirling's record
Shahzad has scored 15 fifty-plus scores in ODIs, the most for AFG breaking Rahmat Shah's record
Gulbadin Naib has broken the record for most ducks (5) in ODIs for AFG, going past Dawlat Zadran's 5
